Question Text: Another term for POTS, or Plain Old Telephone Service, is _______________.
Choices:
a. Public Available Telephone Network
b. Public Switched Telephone Exchange
c. Phone Switched Transport Network
d. Public Switched Telephone Network
e. Public Available Telephone Exchange
LLM Explanation: The term POTS, which stands for Plain Old Telephone Service, is also known as the Public Switched Telephone Network (PSTN). It refers to the traditional landline telephone service.

Question Text: A baud rate is a measurement of the number of ______________________.
Choices:
a. bits that can be sent across a telephone line every minute
b. bytes that can be sent across a telephone line every second
c. bits that can be sent across a telephone line every second
d. bytes that can be sent across a telephone line every minute
LLM Explanation: A baud rate is a measurement of the number of signal or symbol changes that occur per second. It is not directly related to the number of bits or bytes but rather the rate of change of the signal. Each symbol may represent more than one bit, so baud rate and bits per second are not the same.

Question Text: What system did Duke grads build that is still in use today?
Choices:
a. POTS
b. PSTN
c. USENET
d. DSL
LLM Explanation: The system that Duke grads built and is still in use today is USENET, which is a worldwide distributed discussion system available on computers. It was developed in 1979 by Steve Bellovin, Tom Truscott, and Jim Ellis at Duke University.

Question Text: Which device is used to transfer data across a dial-up connection?
Choices:
a. ATM
b. Modem
c. Ethernet cables
d. USENET
LLM Explanation: The device used to transfer data across a dial-up connection is a modem (modulator-demodulator). It modulates digital data from a computer into analog signals for transmission over telephone lines and demodulates incoming analog signals back into digital data.

Question Text: Modems take data that computers can understand and turn them into _____ that can be transmitted over POTS.
Choices:
a. Audible wavelengths
b. Baud rates
c. Modulating electrical charges
d. PSTN
LLM Explanation: Modems modulate digital data from computers into analog signals that can be transmitted over the Public Switched Telephone Network (PSTN) using varying electrical charges.

Choices:
a. Transmission 1
b. Transportation 1
c. Transmission System 1
d. Transportation System 1
LLM Explanation: T1 is short for Transmission 1. It refers to a digital transmission link that operates at 1.544 Mbps.

Question Text: How fast is a T1 line?
Choices:
a. 128 Mb/sec
b. 1.544 Mb/sec
c. 1 Mb/sec
d. 44.763 Mb/sec
LLM Explanation: A T1 line operates at a speed of 1.544 Mb/sec. It is a dedicated digital communication link that carries data, voice, and video at this specific rate.

Question Text: Select all statements that are true of cable internet connections.
Choices:
a. They're wireless connections
b. They're broadband connections
c. They're dial-up connections
d. They're shared bandwidth connections
LLM Explanation:
b. Cable internet connections are broadband connections, providing high-speed internet access through the use of a cable modem.
d. Cable internet connections typically operate on a shared bandwidth setup where multiple users in the same area share the overall bandwidth capacity.

Question Text: What are the subprotocols for PPP (Point to Point Protocol)? Select all that apply.
Choices:
a. FCS
b. LCP
c. Compression
d. NCP
LLM Explanation: The subprotocols for PPP (Point to Point Protocol) include Link Control Protocol (LCP) and Network Control Protocol (NCP). LCP is responsible for establishing, configuring, and testing the data link connection, while NCP is used to negotiate optional configuration parameters and facilitate network layer protocol configuration.

Question Text: What do you call the demarcation point for fiber technologies?
Choices:
a. ONT
b. FTTN
c. FTTX
d. DSLAM
LLM Explanation: The demarcation point for fiber technologies is typically referred to as ONT (Optical Network Terminal). ONT is the device that terminates the fiber optic line in the customer's premises and converts the optical signal into electrical signals for use within the premises.

Choices:
a. Wireless Local Area Network
b. Wireless Area Network
c. Wired Area Network
d. Wide Area Network
LLM Explanation: WAN stands for Wide Area Network, which is a network that covers a broad area, such as across cities, countries, or even globally.

Question Text: In a WAN, what is the area between a demarcation point and the ISP's core network known as?
Choices:
a. a local loop
b. a Local Area Network
c. A local link
d. An access point
LLM Explanation: In a WAN (Wide Area Network), the area between a demarcation point (where the responsibility shifts from the service provider to the customer) and the ISP's core network is known as a local loop.

Question Text: A point-to-point VPN is also known as a ______________.
Choices:
a. port forwarding VPN
b. one-to-many VPN
c. data link VPN
d. site-to-site VPN
LLM Explanation: A point-to-point VPN is commonly referred to as a site-to-site VPN because it connects two separate networks securely over the internet.

Question Text: Who handles sending data from one site to another?
Choices:
a. T-carrier line
b. CTO
c. ISP
d. VPN
LLM Explanation: The Internet Service Provider (ISP) handles sending data from one site to another by providing the necessary network infrastructure and connectivity between different sites.

Question Text: How many address fields does an 802.11 header contain?
LLM Explanation: An 802.11 header contains two address fields: one for the destination address and one for the source address.

Choices:
a. a collision domain
b. a point-to-point wireless connection
c. an example of an ad-hoc network
d. Individual, smaller sections of the overall frequency band used by a wireless network
LLM Explanation: Wireless channels refer to individual, smaller sections of the overall frequency band used by a wireless network to transmit data. These channels help to avoid interference and enable multiple devices to communicate simultaneously.

Question Text: Which of the following frequencies do wireless networks typically operate on? Select all that apply.
LLM Explanation: Wireless networks typically operate on frequencies of 2.4GHz and 5GHz. These frequencies are commonly used for Wi-Fi networks.

Question Text: WPA3 was built with the intention of replacing which protocol?
Choices:
a. WPA2
b. WLAN
c. WEP
d. IEEE 802.11
LLM Explanation: WPA3 was designed to replace WPA2 as the latest security protocol for Wi-Fi networks, providing enhanced security features and stronger encryption methods.

Question Text: An 802.11 frame contains a number of fields. Which field describes the version of 802.11 that is being used?
Choices:
a. Sequence control
b. Frame control
c. Address
d. Duration
LLM Explanation: The field that describes the version of 802.11 being used is the Frame control field. It contains information about the frame type, subtype, and version of 802.11 being used.
